---
# paths: (optional) — scope this rule file to matching files.
#   • Omit entirely → ALWAYS-ON: every rule here loads each session. This is
#     the right default for cross-cutting rules, and is what the four active
#     rule files do (security / cloudformation / scripts / process).
#   • Add globs     → the rules load only when a matching file is in play.
#     Gitignore-style globs; list one or more. Use this when a file's rules
#     are genuinely specific to one area and would be noise elsewhere.
#
# Example — uncomment to scope this file to the IaC templates only:
# paths:
#   - "cloudformation/**"
#   - "docker/**/Dockerfile"
---

# Rules — <topic>

> **Using this template:** copy it to `.claude/rules/<topic>.md` (drop the
> `.example` suffix so it auto-loads), replace the placeholders, and delete
> this blockquote. House style: one **bold imperative directive** per bullet
> with the *why* in the same sentence (so the rule generalizes past the cases
> it lists); add a good/bad snippet **only** for mechanical rules where it
> removes ambiguity — skip it for judgment/behavioral rules; keep it tight,
> since every rule here sits in the context window every session.

- **<Do X, or never do Y>.** <What it covers, concretely — the specific
  things in scope.> <Why — the consequence of getting it wrong, phrased so it
  applies to novel cases too, not just the ones listed.>

- **<A mechanical directive where a snippet earns its place>.** <What + why.>
  ```bash
  <good form>   # good — <one-line reason>
  <bad form>    # bad  — <what breaks, concretely>
  ```

- **<A behavioral / judgment rule>.** <What + why. No code block — an example
  here would be filler.>
